00000,"eeoi":8.592502932687307000,"aer":7.935883112648311000,"soxMt":6.406199999999999000,"sox":0.027115610995476512,"noxMt":65.150000000000000000,"nox":0.275761302543675700,"euEtsDetails":null},{"portName":"Lome","displayOrder":5,"co2":398.669972000000000000,"eeoi":900.441886703188400000,"aer":831.632135431132700000,"soxMt":1.244580000000000000,"sox":2.811026769161973000,"noxMt":12.789800000000000000,"nox":28.887231172144660000,"euEtsDetails":null},{"portName":"Algeciras","displayOrder":6,"co2":1209.277662000000000000,"eeoi":6.613920358802440400,"aer":6.108499385452723000,"soxMt":3.473754000000000000,"sox":0.018999054579469616,"noxMt":38.687700000000000000,"nox":0.211595214817786950,"euEtsDetails":null},{"portName":"Malta (Grand Harbour)","displayOrder":7,"co2":531.400400000000000000,"eeoi":8.867645863041703000,"aer":8.190000236805187000,"soxMt":1.412000000000000000,"sox":0.023562488772336050,"noxMt":16.960000000000000000,"nox":0.283016862307945760,"euEtsDetails":null}]},"remarkList":[{"modifiedDate":"2021-09-17T14:27:19.173","modifiedByFull":"Wright, Bryan","remark":"Operator comments: \n\t\n\tWhat should have been an operationally smooth voyage from Statia to Offshore Lome was hindered by a shoreside pipeline leaking oil from the jetty (twice) into the water around the ship. Initial efforts for cleaning the vessel\u2019s hull and the surrounding water were not effective and resulted in a much longer period of lost time than would be expected in modern ports. Based on an agreement from Vitol to clean the ship after cargo ops, and local pressure due to an imminent gas oil shortage in Togo we agreed to continue discharging cargo. As freeboard increased, the oil stained area of the vessel increased to approximately 4m above the waterline along port, starboard, and bow. The two spills occurred on 11 \u0026 12 July, and cleaning efforts in Lome continued until 03 August. After final cleaning in Lome, a review of the hull\u2019s condition determined she was no longer a pollution threat, but in no condition for international trade. With our options in Lome expended, we sailed the ship to Algeciras for further remedies. In Algeciras the remaining oil was removed, but it was determined both layers of antifouling had been removed in some places and painting would be necessary. Repainting alongside the berth in Algeciras was discussed, but not preferred as this would be considered a temporary fix due to exposure to salt spray. On painting experts\u2019 and insurers\u2019 advice we agreed to bring her into a ship yard for a permanent repair to last until her 2025 dry dock. Vessel will arrive at the Malta Shipyard on 7 September, with expectation for completion by 14 September. Based on initial opinions, and not taking into account any potential claims to Vitol, our insurance claim is expected to cover our losses.\n\t\n\tFinancial changes from prefixture are as follows. I have not included any potential claims to Vitol in this calculation. 19 days in Lome after completion of discharge are included in the final number, with no reimbursement or demurrage estimated.\n-\tFreight increases $68k with 10kmt overage\n-\tIn port operations in Lome are considered interim, 6.3 days of time and bunkers are rebilled for $163k\n-\tBetween Statia loading, and discharge STS offshore Lome we had 13 total port days. This allows for a demurrage claim of $170k (9.2 days @ $18,500).\n-\tPort costs in Statia are $10k less than estimated\n-\tVLSFO cost $162k higher than estimated due to 33 additional port days and cost per mt $24 higher than expected\n\n\t\n\tImprovements: \n\t\n\tWe did have clauses in the CP for oil spills/oil in water, however they were port specific and did not apply to Lome. Therefore, any claim we present is solely against agreements made by Vitol to clean the ship. \n\tIn discussion with lawyers, it appears nearly all of these cases result in the vessel needing to be repainted. With this in mind, we should not have discharged any cargo until the vessel was cleaned to our satisfaction.\n\tFurther to the above, Vitol attempted to wash their hands of this as soon as discharge was completed. Fortunately, we did have agreement in writing for them to clean the ship. In the future we can consider using the cargo as our main source of leverage, but even that strategy comes with its own issues.\n\tFor future port calls in Lome we must take into consideration there is little/no oil response plan. Even oil booms could not be sourced locally."},{"modifiedDate":"2021-06-09T13:03:16.59","modifiedByFull":"Bradbury, Mike","remark":"flat 12.78"}],"offhireList":[{"id":176513,"dateStartUtc":"2021-07-20T13:06:00","dateEndUtc":"2021-09-17T10:42:00","days":58.9,"displayOrder":0,"offhireReason":"Other","remark":"Unplanned - Down time for oil pollution removal","offhireBunkerList":[{"id":8626,"gradeName":"LSBF","quantity":486.7,"price":582.95,"displayOrder":0},{"id":8627,"gradeName":"LSBF","quantity":107.4,"price":522.0,"displayOrder":1},{"id":8628,"gradeName":"LSGO","quantity":26.36,"price":500.29,"displayOrder":2},{"id":8632,"gradeName":"LSGO","quantity":62.74,"price":600.08,"displayOrder":3}]}],"tcNumber":null,"tcOutIdEncrypted":null,"tcReletDetail":null}